This place has gone downhill over the past year. Everything from portion size to preparation to packaging to flavor, the bopNgrill on Belmont is not hitting the mark. There have been plenty of mishaps, but today I ordered a side of fresh kimchi and was given the old cooked kind with the stinky, funky flavors. Don’t get me wrong. I like that type of kimchi, too, but for soups and stews. Also, they gave me half a portion of fries and then placed it on the bottom of the bag so it could get smooshed and soggy. Nice going. Oh, and the fire chicken is no longer spicy. What?! You don’t think I can handle the hot flavors? Oh, and I forgot to mention, they put the not-so-spicy and dry chicken on top of the salad. What happen to the awesome plastic containers they had which kept everything a bit separated. The salad was super soggy.  Sorry, but not sorry. The one up by Loyola is far superior. I hope the manager takes a little vacation up to the Loyola location to see what awesomeness is cooking there.

The food here is quite tasty and I only have one complaint: the lack of availability of the Philly Bulkogi Eggrolls - their most unique menu item. Sure, restaurants run out of items now and again, but I've been to this location several times now and it seems to be a recurring theme.  I paced my most recent order on a Friday around 6:30pm and was told they were out of the eggrolls. Now, they only offer these eggrolls Friday-Sunday and the limit is one order per person. How can they already be out at prime dinner hour on Friday? Maybe they were extremely busy I thought? But when I walked in at 6:45pm there was only one other customer in the restaurant! If this occurred at the end of the night, the outage would be more understandable. It seems they need to rethink their supply chain management... but what is odd about this is the fact that the main ingredient in these (the beef bulkogi) is still available to order.  An employee mentioned something about cost as an excuse. I doubt you have an item on your menu that you are losing money on... If so, you should raise the price - basic supply & demand. She also mentioned famous BBQ restaurants were customers encounter this debacle. However, I'm familiar with such spots like Franklin's BBQ in Austin - they have their supply chain down to a science and so rarely run out of meat until the very end of the day. BobNGrill is great, but I've yet to see a line out front...  Do you only have time to make 10 eggrolls per day? I'd genuinely like to find out what is causing this bottleneck.  Again, great food but questionable business practice with the Philly Bulkogi Eggrolls.
